'''Clifford Ando''' (born 1969) is an American classicist who specializes in [[Roman law]] and [[Religion in ancient Rome|religion]]. His work deals primarily with law, religion, and government in the [[Roman Empire|Imperial era]], particularly issues of [[Roman citizenship]], legal pluralism, and legal procedure. In the [[history of law]], his work addresses the relations among [[Civil law (legal system)|civil law]], [[public law]], and [[international law]].<ref>The Law School at the University of Chicago, [http://www.law.uchicago.edu/faculty/ando Clifford Ando.]</ref>
Ando is a professor in the Department of Classics, History and Law and in the College at the [[University of Chicago]].<ref>"Note on Contributors," in ''The Roman Foundation of the Law of Nations'' (Oxford University Press, 2010), p. vii.</ref> He is a research fellow in the Department of Classics and World Languages at the University of South Africa, and the recipient of several fellowships, grants, and prizes.<ref>The Department of Classics faculty bio, [http://classics.uchicago.edu/faculty/ando Clifford Ando.]</ref> He has held fellowship and visiting professorships in Canada, France, Germany, New Zealand, and South Africa.<ref>The Law School at the University of Chicago, [http://www.law.uchicago.edu/faculty/ando Clifford Ando] and [http://www.law.uchicago.edu/node/5539/activities Additional activities.]</ref> He earned his doctorate from the [[University of Michigan]] in 1996, and his bachelor's degree from [[Princeton University]] in 1990.<ref>The Law School at the University of Chicago, Clifford Ando: [http://www.law.uchicago.edu/node/5539/cv Curriculum Vitae.]</ref>
In 2008, he was among faculty members who questioned the establishment of the [[Milton Friedman Institute for Research in Economics|Milton Friedman Institute]] at the University of Chicago.<ref>[http://www.miltonfriedmancores.org/cores/letter-from-faculty/ Letter from Faculty.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120311032305/http://www.miltonfriedmancores.org/cores/letter-from-faculty/ |date=2012-03-11 }}</ref>
==Major works== * ''Imperial Ideology and Provincial Loyalty in the Roman Empire'' (2000), winner of the 2003 Goodwin Award from the American Philological Association * Editor, ''Roman Religion'' (2003) * Co-editor with [[Jörg Rüpke]], ''Religion and Law in Classical and Christian Rome'' (2006) * ''The Matter of the Gods'' (2008) * ''Law, Language and Empire in the Roman Tradition'' (2011) * ''Le Droit et l'Empire. Invention juridique et réalités politiques à Rome'' (2012) * ''Imperial Rome: The Critical Century (A.D. 193–284)'' (2012) * ''Religion et gouvernement dans l'Empire romain'' (2012) Ando has also published numerous articles, essays, and reviews.
