{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2013}} The [[marquess]] '''Giacomo Arditi''' of Castelvetere ([[Presicce]], March 21, 1815 – July 1891) was an [[Italians|Italian]] historian, economist and writer, nephew of the archaeologist [[Michele Arditi]].
Giacomo Arditi is best known for his work ''La Corografia fisica et storica della provincia di Terra d'Otranto'', the most ponderous encyclopedic work that has ever succeeded to provide a complete portrait of the province of [[Salento]], the [[unification of Italy]], and the proclamation of Rome as the capital of the [[Kingdom of Italy]]. Arditi was the member of numerous academies, member of the Archaeological Commission of the province of [[Lecce]], being royal inspector of antiquities and monuments, President of the Provincial Deputation and Vice-intendent of the [[Gallipoli, Apulia|District of Gallipoli]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Personaggi illustri: Giacomo Arditi |url=http://www.comune.presicce.le.it/citta_territorio/personaggi_illustri.php |publisher=Comune di Presicce |accessdate=November 30, 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203030708/http://www.comune.presicce.le.it/citta_territorio/personaggi_illustri.php |archivedate=December 3, 2013 |df=mdy }}</ref>
== Works == * ''La Corografia fisica et storica della provincia di Terra d'Otranto'' (1849) * ''La Leuca Salentina'' (1875)
